10PM GMT (it would be later, but I have to stand some chance of going to my own event)<br>
Location: The East Commonlands/North Ro tunnel, the large part with the camp fire.<br>
Food and drink will be there (no need to bring anything yourself)<br>
ALL alignments and races welcome, no one will be turned away.<br>
<br>
I can do this one of two ways...<br>
<br>
1. /say, /shout. The languages used would be Teir'Dal, Human and Elvish. Everyone does their best to at least one of those languages. It's good, because everyone has to be there, it creates a sense of community, afterall, it is an event for meeting people also. It's bad, because of the language barrier.<br>
<br>
2. A channel could be set up. This would eliminate the language barrier, but would take away the usefulness of emotes and would make it a very abstract situation (ie people could listen in from across the continent, with no requirement to be there... this is not something I particularly want to happen) To be honest, I prefer the /say and /shout method, but if the languages are too complex (I want this event to be open to as many people as possible, newbies and veterans alike) then I'll use the channel method.<br>
<br>
The order of speaking isn't concrete. We'll start with a general subject (probably dragons knowing me) and work down from there, using links where possible. No chronological order. If you think you know something else, you can grumble and get next shot at telling your own version of the story. Feel free to argue, that's half the fun. Basically, keep telling stories until we run out of people or run out of stories. If you feel the need to step up to a podium, I'm sure something like levitate can be used to show you're telling a story (I'll deal with the bat wings myself if they are needed)<br>
<br>
Again, ANYONE who wants to tell a story about the planet, the gods, a brave hero, a great villian, wants to learn more about Norrath lore, or just wants something to do to have a break from endless xp grinding, just come along. I'm sure there'll be something to do there  <br>
 <br>
